Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Remove the @British beef roasting joint{400%g} from your fridge, pop it onto a large #baking tray{}, drizzle with @olive oil{} and rub three quarters of the garlic over the beef. Set aside and allow it come up to room temperature.

Next, pour enough @oil{} into a deep baking tray to cover the bottom and pop into the hot oven.

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Peel and chop the @potatoes{450%g}(peeled and chopped) into 4cm chunks. Boil the potatoes for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges are soft.

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed). Roughly chop the @hazelnuts{25%g}(roughly chopped).

When the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{} and sprinkle on a third of the @plain flour{3/4%tbsp}.

Shake to fluff up the potatoes, then carefully add them to the hot baking tray, turning in the oil.

Season with salt, then roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{45-50%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, wrap a rasher of @British streaky bacon{4%rashers} around each @British honey mustard sausages{4} - starting at the top, spiral the bacon down the sausage so it covers the whole thing. Pop onto one side of another #baking tray{}, then set aside for now.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Season the beef with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{20-25%minutes} or ~{30-35%minutes} (depending on size) for medium-rare. Add an extra ~{5%minutes} if you like your beef more well done.

Meanwhile, trim the @parsnip{1}(trimmed) and @carrot{2}(trimmed), then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop them into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons. Add to the other side of the pigs in blankets tray, drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast the veg and pigs in blankets on the bottom shelf until the veg is tender and the sausages are golden brown and cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The sausages are cooked when no longer pink in the middle. Cook bacon thoroughly.

Meanwhile, pop a medium #saucepan{} on medium-high heat. Melt the @butter{30%g}, then stir in the @plain flour{2%tbsp}. Continue to stir until combined, you've made a roux! Cook, stirring, until the roux is a medium brown colour, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Gradually stir in the @water for the gravy{400%ml}, then add the @chicken stock paste{20%g} and bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that form.

Lower the heat and simmer, stirring occasionally, until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{15-20%minutes}. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a medium #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the green beans and stir-fry until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in the remaining garlic, then turn the heat down to medium and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add a splash of @water{} and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Cook until the beans are tender, ~{4-5%minutes}, then remove from the heat and cover to keep warm.

Once the beef is cooked, rest, wrapped loosely in #foil{}, for at least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.

> IMPORTANT: The beef is safe to eat when the outside is browned and cooked.

Once roasted, drizzle the @honey{1%tbsp} over the veg and toss together.

Slice the beef and share between your plates. Serve with the roast potatoes, root veg, green beans and pigs in blankets alongside.

Scatter the hazelnuts over the beans and pour over the gravy to finish.

Enjoy!